**How to maximize Google Chrome**

| OS | Quick keyboard shortcut | Mouse method |
|----|------------------------|--------------|
| **Windows** | `Alt + Space`, then **X** (or simply `Win + ↑` when the window is selected) | Click the **Restore/Maximize** button (the square in the upper‑right corner) or double‑click the title bar |
| **macOS** | `⌃ + ⌘ + F` (Control‑Command‑F) | Click the green traffic‑light button in the upper‑left corner or double‑click the title bar |
| **Linux (GNOME/KDE)** | `Alt + Space`, then **X** (or `Super + ↑`) | Click the maximize button in the window’s title bar |

### One‑click script (Windows PowerShell)

If you prefer an automated way, run this short script. It will locate the Chrome window and maximize it.

```powershell
# Requires no extra modules
Add-Type @"
using System;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
public class Win {
    [DllImport("user32.dll")]
    public static extern IntPtr FindWindow(string lpClassName, string lpWindowName);
    [DllImport("user32.dll")]
    public static extern bool ShowWindow(IntPtr hWnd, int nCmdShow);
}
"@

$chrome = [Win]::FindWindow("Chrome_WidgetWin_1", $null)   # Chrome’s window class
if ($chrome -ne [IntPtr]::Zero) {
    # 3 = SW_MAXIMIZE
    [Win]::ShowWindow($chrome, 3)
    "Chrome maximized."
} else {
    "Chrome window not found."
}
``  
Save as `maximize-chrome.ps1` and run it in PowerShell (`.\maximize-chrome.ps1`).  

*(On macOS/Linux you’d use AppleScript or `wmctrl` respectively, but the keyboard shortcuts above work instantly.)*

